title.narrative: OUTPUT 1.5 NUTRITION IN EMERGENCIES

description.narrative: Output 5 (Nutrition in emergencies): Governments and partners at national and sub-national level have increasing evidence to address the impact of climate change on nutrition and improved capacity to prepare for, respond to, and recover from disasters in a timely and coordinated manner to ensure the nutrition status of the population including the most vulnerable groups is protected, which contributes to Early Detection And Treatment Of Malnutrition, Early Detection And Treatment Of Malnutrition (Covid), Nutrition In Early Childhood, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Evaluations, Research And Data, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Pregnant and lactating mothers, children aged under 5 years, and adolescents, including the most vulnerable groups utilize quality and equitable essential nutrition services and adopt appropriate diet and care practices

description.narrative: UNICEF continued to demonstrate strong technical leadership in nutrition in emergencies, serving as the co-lead for the nutrition sub-cluster led by the Ministry of Health. In 2021,UNICEF made dedicated efforts to strengthen the Government and partners’ capacity on nutrition emergency preparedness by putting in place sustainable systems to support effective nutrition emergency preparedness and response. This includes the development of the training curricula and online learning materials on nutrition in emergencies and nutrition emergency contingency plans at the provincial level. UNICEF continued to lead the risk communication and community engagement on nutrition during the COVID-19 pandemic. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:28/11/2021
